io.github.utk003.json.traditional.node

Class JSONValue

  • java.lang.Object
    • io.github.utk003.json.traditional.node.JSONValue
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    JSONArray, JSONNumber, JSONObject, JSONPrimitive, JSONString

    public abstract class JSONValue
extends Object
    An abstract class that represents a node for a JSON tree.

    A JSONValue can represent an object, an array, a string, a number, a boolean (primitive), or null (primitive). The specific type is stored as a JSONValue.ValueType.

    A JSONValue stores its element type, its path in the JSON tree, and any children elements depending on its specific JSON type. Specifically, this element will have children if and only if it is also a JSONStorageElement, with the parameterized type being either a String or an Integer.

    A JSONValue also provides utility methods for printing out the JSON it represents, both in a nicely formatted form as well as in a condensed form that has no whitespace.

    Lastly, the findElements(String) method can be used to find all elements in the tree whose paths match a specific path expression.

    Version:
    February 23, 2021

      • findElements

        public final Collection<JSONValue> findElements(String path)
        Returns a Collection of JSONValues corresponding to all elements in the JSON tree rooted at this JSONValue whose path in the tree matches the targt path specified by the path argument.

        The path consists of JSON object keys and array indices separated by periods (.) for the keys and surrounded by brackets ([]) for the indices. Additionally, an asterisk (*) can be used to designate a wildcard element, which means any child at that level will match that specific part of the path. Lastly, if ROOT_PATH is provided as the first step in the path, then the path will be treated as "anchored". In other words, the path will be treated as an absolute path from the root of the tree. If the root path is not included, then any element whose path matches the target path (from any point along the path of the element) will match with the target path.

        Parameters:
        path - The target path along the JSON tree
        Returns:
        A Collection of all JSONValues whose path matches the target path
